  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Provides international standards for preventing money laundering\n- 40 recommendations widely adopted by countries worldwide\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigations\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Establishes banking regulations to prevent money laundering\n\n4. The Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing to combat money laundering\n\n5. The Palermo Convention (2000)\n- UN treaty addressing organized crime and money laundering\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Conduct due diligence checks\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
